definitions.definition: ( transitive , obsolete or poetic ) Especially when describing animals : to consume , devour , or eat .
( transitive ) To chafe or irritate ; to worry .
( transitive ) To make rough , to agitate or disturb ; to cause to ripple .
examples: to fret the surface of water

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) In the form fret out : to squander , to waste .
( ambitransitive ) To gnaw ; to consume , to eat away .
( ambitransitive ) To be chafed or irritated ; to be angry or vexed ; to utter peevish expressions through irritation or worry .
( intransitive ) To be worn away ; to chafe; to fray .
examples: A wristband frets on the edges.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To be anxious , to worry .
( intransitive ) To be agitated ; to rankle ; to be in violent commotion .
examples: Rancour frets in the malignant breast.

definitions.definition: ( intransitive , brewing , oenology ) To have secondary fermentation ( fermentation occurring after the conversion of sugar to alcohol in beers and wine ) take place.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To decorate or ornament , especially with an interlaced or interwoven pattern , or ( architecture ) with carving or relief ( raised ) work .
( transitive ) To form a pattern on; to variegate .
( transitive ) To cut through with a fretsaw , to create fretwork .

To press down the string behind a fret.
